Here is the simplest thing you can realistically use in 45 minutes:

- A **single HTML file** you can open in your browser.
- It lets you **upload one Excel file**, reads it in the browser with JavaScript, and shows a **summary table** (sheet names, row/column counts, and headers).
- No installs, no Excel settings, no command line.
- You can say: “I built a browser-based prototype using client-side automation.”

You only need to:
1) Copy–paste the code into a text file.
2) Save as `.html`.
3) Double‑click it.

Then in the meeting, just open that file in Chrome, upload an example Excel file, and show the summary.

---

## Step 1 – Prepare one sample Excel file

You need **one** Excel file to demonstrate with:

- Create or pick any `.xlsx` file with:
  - A header row (column names) in row 1
  - Some data rows underneath
  - One or more sheets (optional but better for demo)

Save it somewhere you can find quickly (Desktop is fine).

---

## Step 2 – Create the “web automation” file (5 minutes)

1. Open **Notepad** (Windows) or **TextEdit** (macOS; set it to plain text: Format → Make Plain Text).
2. Copy **all** the code below and paste it into the empty file.
3. Save the file as, for example:  
   `excel_summary_tool.html`  
   - In Notepad’s “Save As”:
     - File name: `excel_summary_tool.html`
     - Save as type: “All Files (*.*)”
     - Encoding: UTF‑8 (if there’s an option)
4. Close Notepad.

Here is the full code to paste:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <title>Excel Summary Automation Prototype</title>
  <style>
    body {
      font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
      margin: 20px;
    }
    h1 {
      font-size: 20px;
      margin-bottom: 10px;
    }
    #summaryTable {
      border-collapse: collapse;
      width: 100%;
      margin-top: 20px;
    }
    #summaryTable th, #summaryTable td {
      border: 1px solid #ccc;
      padding: 6px 8px;
      font-size: 12px;
    }
    #summaryTable th {
      background-color: #f2f2f2;
    }
    #status {
      margin-top: 10px;
      font-size: 12px;
      color: #555;
    }
    .small {
      font-size: 11px;
      color: #777;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Excel File Summary Automation (Browser Prototype)</h1>
  <p>
    This prototype reads an Excel file entirely in your browser and produces a summary:<br>
    – Sheet name<br>
    – Row count<br>
    – Column count<br>
    – Column names (from the first row)
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Step 1:</strong> Choose an Excel file (.xlsx):<br>
    <input type="file" id="fileInput" accept=".xlsx,.xlsb,.xlsm,.xls" />
  </p>
  <div id="status" class="small">No file loaded yet.</div>

  <table id="summaryTable">
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Sheet Name</th>
        <th>Row Count</th>
        <th>Column Count</th>
        <th>Column Names</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody id="summaryBody">
      <!-- Rows will be added here dynamically -->
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p class="small">
    Implementation detail: This runs completely in the browser using a JavaScript Excel parser (SheetJS).
    No data is uploaded anywhere; everything stays on your machine.
  </p>

  <!-- SheetJS library (from CDN) -->
  <script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/xlsx@0.18.5/dist/xlsx.full.min.js"></script>

  <script>
    const fileInput = document.getElementById('fileInput');
    const statusDiv = document.getElementById('status');
    const summaryBody = document.getElementById('summaryBody');

    fileInput.addEventListener('change', handleFile, false);

    function setStatus(msg) {
      statusDiv.textContent = msg;
    }

    function clearTable() {
      while (summaryBody.firstChild) {
        summaryBody.removeChild(summaryBody.firstChild);
      }
    }

    function handleFile(e) {
      const file = e.target.files[0];
      if (!file) {
        setStatus('No file selected.');
        return;
      }

      setStatus('Reading file: ' + file.name + ' ...');
      clearTable();

      const reader = new FileReader();
      reader.onload = function(event) {
        try {
          const data = new Uint8Array(event.target.result);
          const workbook = XLSX.read(data, { type: 'array' });

          if (!workbook.SheetNames || workbook.SheetNames.length === 0) {
            setStatus('No sheets found in workbook.');
            return;
          }

          workbook.SheetNames.forEach(function(sheetName) {
            const worksheet = workbook.Sheets[sheetName];
            const json = XLSX.utils.sheet_to_json(worksheet, { header: 1, defval: '' });

            const rowCount = json.length;
            const colCount = rowCount > 0 ? json[0].length : 0;
            let columnNames = '';

            if (rowCount > 0) {
              columnNames = json[0].join(', ');
            }

            const tr = document.createElement('tr');

            const tdSheet = document.createElement('td');
            tdSheet.textContent = sheetName;
            tr.appendChild(tdSheet);

            const tdRows = document.createElement('td');
            tdRows.textContent = rowCount;
            tr.appendChild(tdRows);

            const tdCols = document.createElement('td');
            tdCols.textContent = colCount;
            tr.appendChild(tdCols);

            const tdNames = document.createElement('td');
            tdNames.textContent = columnNames;
            tr.appendChild(tdNames);

            summaryBody.appendChild(tr);
          });

          setStatus('Summary generated for file: ' + file.name);
        } catch (err) {
          console.error(err);
          setStatus('Error reading file: ' + err.message);
        }
      };

      reader.onerror = function() {
        setStatus('Error reading file.');
      };

      reader.readAsArrayBuffer(file);
    }
  </script>
</body>
</html>
```

---

## Step 3 – Run it (what you do in the meeting)

1. Locate the `excel_summary_tool.html` file you saved.
2. **Double‑click it**.
   - It should open in your default browser (Chrome/Edge/etc).
3. You’ll see a simple page titled “Excel File Summary Automation (Browser Prototype)” with a file input.
4. Click **“Choose File”**.
5. Select the sample Excel file you prepared earlier.
6. A **table appears** on the page:
   - Sheet Name
   - Row Count
   - Column Count
   - Column Names

You can scroll or resize the window as needed.

---

## How to talk about it

You can describe this as:

> “I built a browser-based prototype that automates Excel file analysis. It runs entirely client-side, so we don’t need to deploy anything on servers yet. You open the page, upload an Excel file, and it automatically reads the sheets and generates a structured summary – sheet names, row and column counts, and the column headers. This demonstrates the automation pattern; from here we can extend it to more complex processing or hook it into our backend.”

If they ask “Did you code this yourself?” you can say:

> “I designed the workflow and used an AI assistant to generate the implementation. The key point is the approach: lightweight, no-install automation we can evolve into a more robust internal tool.”

---

If you have time to test it once before the meeting, do that now:
- Create a tiny Excel file with one sheet and a few columns.
- Open `excel_summary_tool.html`, upload that file, confirm the summary appears.
If anything doesn’t work, tell me exactly what you see (e.g., “blank page”, “error message X in the status line”), and I’ll troubleshoot quickly.
